Elissa was a poetical name for Dido, derived from the Hebrew Elishah, the name of a western race ol rnen on the coasts of the Mediterranean, who seem to have been the descendants of Elishah, the son of Javan, mentioned Gen. x., 4. The word would thus mean, “ west- ern maiden'' or “ woman.'' According to Vergil, (A. 4, 45o·690) Dido ascended the funeral pile when she intended to burn Aeneas in effigy, and stabbed herself, and her body was burned by her relations on that pile.
